
[1]night

   NIGHT, n. [The sense may be dark, black, or it may be the decline of
   the day, from declining, departing.]

   1. That part of the natural day when the sun is beneath the horizon, or
   the time from sunset to sunrise.

   2. The time after the close of life; death. John 9.

   She closed her eyes in everlasting night.

   3. A state of ignorance; intellectual and moral darkness; heathenish
   ignorance. Romans 13.

   4. Adversity; a state of affliction and distress. Isaiah 21.

   5. Obscurity; a state of concealment from the eye or the mind;
   unintelligibleness.

   Nature and natures works lay hid in night.

   In the night, suddenly; unexpectedly. Luke 12.

   To-night, in this night. To-night the moon will be eclipsed.
